			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I hate to go against the moderators on this one, but I hope you'll excuse me.  I thought that 240 posts was a bit much to wade through for the average board reader, and I think what I have to say will interest the vast majority of you.  So without further delay...
<br />

<br />

<br />
Hey Everyone, 
<br />

<br />
Sorry I didn’t have a chance to post on this earlier, but I wanted to make sure I had all my ducks in a row first.  I hope this post will give you all a better understanding of the reasons for the change to reclaim energy.
<br />

<br />
Here’s a breakdown of the 4 caster classes in terms of personal mana regeneration at level 65.  The numbers are very different for a fully buffed raid situation, but as pet cannibalize is rarely used in a raid situation, I don’t think it’s an appropriate comparison.
<br />

<br />
Enchanter:
<br />
Voice of Quellious: 18/tick
<br />
Gather Mana: 4.9/tick (5000 mana Average/604.8 tick reuse)
<br />
Total: 22.9/tick
<br />

<br />
Necromancer:
<br />
Seduction of Saryrn: 50/tick
<br />
Total: 50/tick
<br />

<br />
Wizard:
<br />
Harvest + Harvest of Druzzil: 7.5/tick (376 + 475/600 Tick reuse)
<br />
Force Shield: 2/tick
<br />
Allegiant Familiar: 8/tick
<br />
Total: 17.5/tick
<br />

<br />
Mage w/o Pet Canni:
<br />
Xegony’s: 6/tick
<br />
Water Elemental Form: 4/tick
<br />
Mystical Trans. Rod: 7.2/tick (360Mana/50 Ticks) The Hp trade off really doesn’t come into play here, since Xegony’s also has enough health regeneration to recover the HP spent before the 5 minute reuse timer is up.
<br />
Total: 17.2/tick
<br />

<br />
So we’ve got:
<br />
1)	Necro – 50/tick
<br />
2)	Enchanter – 22.9/tick
<br />
3)	Wizard 17.5/tick
<br />
4)	Mage 17.2/tick
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Now let’s look at a mage using pet Cannibalize:
<br />

<br />
400 Mana base cost
<br />
-13% for SCM and spec check (Note, this is with the mage specialized in something other then conjuration)
<br />
-13% average for Summoning Efficiency Focus
<br />
Equals: 296 Mana actual cost
<br />

<br />
Reclaim Energy returns 10% of the HP of the pet
<br />
Rathe’s Son = 4800 hp base
<br />
480 Mana returned
<br />
Net mana gained per cast: 184
<br />

<br />
With Summoning Haste and appropriate AA you end up with a 50% reduction in cast time:
<br />
Base cast time: 10 seconds
<br />
Modified cast time: 5 seconds
<br />
Recovery time: 2.25 seconds
<br />

<br />
184Mana/7.25 Cast time = 25.4 Mana/second
<br />

<br />
or 152 Mana a tick
<br />

<br />
If you start focusing the pet, it gets even bigger:
<br />
Summoner’s Boon: 193mana/tick
<br />
Dark Minion: 211mana/tick
<br />
Minion of Eternity: 271mana/tick
<br />
Ritual Summoning: 297mana/tick
<br />

<br />
But let’s just look at the unfocused for now:
<br />

<br />
Mage w/o Pet Canni:
<br />
Total: 17.2/tick
<br />

<br />
Mage w/ Pet Canni:
<br />
Total: 169.2/tick
<br />

<br />
So let’s look at that comparison again an lets give all the other casters their med bonus, since they don’t have to be up casting spells while they’re doing this:
<br />

<br />
1)	Mage 169.2/tick
<br />
2)	Necro 71/tick
<br />
3)	Enchanter 43.9/tick
<br />
4)	Wizard 38.2/tick
<br />

<br />
Clearly one of these values is out of place, and that’s why we felt it necessary to change this ability.  I know this isn’t necessarily going to make anyone agree with the change that didn’t before, but at least you know our rational for changing it.  Also, since we’re not trying to nerf mage’s contributions to a group, I’m planning on upping the mana regeneration for the Xegony line to 6/8 mana regeneration instead of 4/6.  While I know this isn’t exactly a fair trade, 169 mana/tick was pretty ridiculous.  I don’t foresee a decrease in mages’ desirability in groups or raids because of this change.
<br />

<br />
If anyone finds errors in my math, please post them.
<br />

<br />
As always, feedback on this is most welcome.
<br />

<br />
-Rytan</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
