				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think one of the biggest things that isn't really correct about those numbers is that all of them are "passive" regeneration (don't require any activity directly from the player, don't interefere with other fields), while pet canni left the mage without a pet, unable to cast anything else during the time, subject to interrupts, fizzles, required a base mana to start from. Although, yes, we did have a high FT equivalent, that was only when activley canni'ing.
<br />

<br />
I felt the ability relativley balanced; it gave mages a way to reduce down time, was "flavoured" and unique to mages, it was an interesting tactical consideration and it didn't have a huge impact on the game (not something that "screamed" nerf me, obviously, since this has been going of for a long time). Perhaps, as a mage who used it alot, I'm biased, and the forumlae for the gains produced by the effect should be changed, but I don't think it should be removed all together. 
<br />

<br />
Did it really allow us to do things we shouldn't have been able to ?
<br />

<br />

<br />
The AA costs as mentioned above should also be taken into account, as well as the fact that this hits mages from 49 up, and not just the level 65 mages with Eform3. They went from 0FT, to what canni gave them, then at 56 get rods... Water III doesnt stack with a horse... another good point which was brought up.
<br />

<br />
Edit: By passive, I also mean that most of them cast the spell, get the mana, and don't need to worry about it from then untill (x) minutes later. We keep canni'ing. Harvest is click and forget, so fairly "passive", and Saryn's, I agree, is active as well.<br />_________________<br />"The ability to quote is a serviceable substitute for wit."
