				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The other peak in the comparison is at level 56/57 where: 
<br />

<br />
Necro: 31 
<br />
Enchanter: 12 
<br />
Wizard: 10.6 
<br />
Mage 4.5 
<br />

<br />
w/Canni Mage = 125.9 unfocused pet 
<br />

<br />
Also, my second post is a touch off. The mana cost for casting the rod is modified by SCM, specs and mana pres as well. 
<br />
I think we can ignore that though, as the difference isn't going to make or break the comparison. We can probably factor it out with the cost of casting the buffs themselves. 
<br />

<br />
There's a multitude of scenarios you can set this up in including horse, horse, with an enchanter, without an enchanter, with bard, without bard. But none of them are going to change the fact that you end up with some crazy potential mana regen from pet canni. 
<br />

<br />
I don't think the AA cost should necessarily be factored in, as there's several other areas where mages are going to get a greater gain from certain AA’s purchased over another class. 
<br />

<br />
Another thing to consider is the potential effect on future mage abilities. This problem only gets worse every time I add a pet with more hit points. One way or another, I'd have to factor it in as part of mage's potential. The most likely candidate for this would be to make summon spells cost an inordinate amount of mana to compensate for the mana you can get back from them. I think it's a much healthier solution to remove this ability and then consider the balance of mages without it. 
<br />

<br />
I hope most of you agree. 
<br />

<br />
Transon's should be bumped to 6, and Xegony's to 8 next test patch.
<br />

<br />
-Ryan</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
