			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Your decision to remove the ability to reclaim pets for mana, is not only an insult to the class, but also a deathblow to Mages' ability to provide useful dps in most situations.  This goes beyond the simple fact that 150mana/tic regens numbers supposedly can be reached.  
<br />

<br />
First of all, those numbers are RARELY reached.  Secondly, this supposedly unbalancing regen is only obtainable by actively casting spells, as fast as your RL dexterity allows, AND you cannot perform ANY OTHER FUNCTIONS WHILE DOING SO.  This last fact alone seperates it from the other forms of innate mana regen.  Fourthly, your efforts to sneak this *fix* in, have effectively zero'd out any trust the Magician community had, not only concerning your ethics, but regarding our faith that you have the ability to discern what is truly *balanced*.  
<br />

<br />
While as developers, you <span style="font-style: italic">will</span> have some inherent insight that players don't, you lack the <span style="font-style: italic">years</span> of experience many players possess, and as a result dont realize that what may appear on paper to be *imbalanced*, was actually one of the few saving graces to playing a mage.  
<br />

<br />
You quote that mages are *second* to wizards in DPS.  However what you do not mention, is that at least 4 other classes achieve this as well.  The problem, is that those other classes provide so much UTILITY, that their worth far exceeds any benefit a Magician can provide.  I will not go into specifics, this information has been quoted over and over at our forum.  Furthermore, mages achieving second place in DPS only occurs when conditions are 100% favorable to our class.  Meaning, no AOE bosses, no situations where push control is critical, no situations where deaths(pet) cause adds,  and no mobs that are highly resistant to either magic/fire.  So basically, we can assume that at the very least, 30 percent of boss mobs innately reduce mage DPS to not only behind a wizard's, but most melee classes as well.  What then is the function of a mage on these occasions? Cast DS? No.  Provide mod rods? That requires 1 mage at the beginning of the encounter, no.  Summon pet weapons? Same as above.  Unfortunately, those are the only 3 benefits a mage can provide, and unfortunately as well, they are trivial. 
<br />

<br />
If you remove pet cannibalization without compensation that provides *true* benefit to the class, mages will simply become un-needed.  It becomes extremely difficult to compete with other class' DPS without canni.  Improving XPG to 6/8 will do nothing.  We all know that is simply an attempt to cover up this gaping wound with merely a bandaid.  
<br />

<br />
The Dev's have two options.  Either increase Magician DPS via pets or nukes, or provide the class with a utility role that balances our reduced ability to do damage.  Simply removing canni because you think 3 minutes of 150mana/tic is wrong, will only widen the gap between where the Mage class is, and where we all know it should be.    
<br />

<br />
Cito, 65th Magician of Mithaniel Marr</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
